g.text: Step 2: Save Current Registers to PCB
Step 5: Load CR3 (if page dirs differ)

ul.li: CPU pushes SS, ESP, EFLAGS, CS, EIP
If privilege change: stack switch via TSS

div.p: offset 0: EAX (4 bytes) offset 4: ECX offset 8: EDX offset 12: EBX offset 16: ESP (kernel ESP) offset 20: EBP offset 24: ESI offset 28: EDI offset 32: EIP offset 36: CS offset 40: EFLAGS
CRITICAL: If TSS.ESP0 is stale, userkernel transition will corrupt stack!
Ring 3 Ring 0: CPU loads SS:ESP from TSS automatically.

ul.li: Kernel threads share kernel page dir
Use PCID if available to avoid flush

ol.li: If CS.RPL changes: pops ESP, SS

div.p: Color Key: Yellow: Interrupt source Purple: CPU/Stack state Green: PCB/Success state Red: MODIFIED/Critical write Blue: User mode code
CS:EIP = 0x08:kernel_code ESP = kernel_stack_ptr EAX..EDI = current_values CR3 = current_pdir

Same process or kernel threads share the same page directory. No TLB flush needed.
asm restore_context: mov eax, [next] ; get next PCB mov esp, [eax+PCB.regs] pop gs, fs, es, ds ; restore segs popa ; restore general add esp, 8 ; skip error+vec iret ; RESTORE ALL!
EAX = next_pcb.regs.eax ECX = next_pcb.regs.ecx ... ESP = next_pcb.regs.esp EIP = next_pcb.regs.eip CS = next_pcb.regs.cs EFLAGS = next_pcb.regs.eflags CR3 = next_pcb.cr3
ESP [ SS ] if privilege change [ ESP ] user stack pointer [ EFLAGS ] IF restored here [ CS ] 0x1B (ring 3) or 0x08 [ EIP ] instruction pointer
CS:EIP = 0x1B:user_code RING 3! ESP = user_stack_ptr SS = 0x23 (user data) CR3 = 0x00200000 EFLAGS.IF = 1 (interrupts on)
